equation_narrative.headline: Polar representation shifts to charged prediction as aspartate-specific features activate late
equation_narrative.story: Position 58 in ubiquitin sits in a polar-rich local environment (GRTLS[D]YNIQK) with three structural contacts. Through layers 1-23, the model assembles a representation that fluctuates between hydrophobic (A, L) and polar (S, T) character, reflecting the mixed chemistry of nearby residues. The logit lens shows serine leading at 22.6% initially, rising to 46.6% by L26, but this reflects the polar character of the representation, not a prediction. The decisive shift occurs at L30-33: aspartate-specific MLP neurons (N30:4229, N31:2506) and attention features (F33:2787) activate strongly, driving D from 5.8% at L29 to 66.7% at L33. The model correctly identifies this as a negatively charged position despite limited structural evidence.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 gather local sequence context with minimal structural or co-evolutionary signal. Only 3 structural contacts are present, and no co-evolving positions are detected. Early attention features (F1:9146, F1:5480) encode the local sequence environment. The representation character oscillates: serine dominates initially (22.6% at L0), then shifts through hydrophobic residues (H peaks at 29.0% at L3-4, then A/L alternate through L20), before returning to serine (26.3% at L23). These fluctuations reflect the model reading mixed chemical signals—polar neighbors (S57, T55) versus hydrophobic contacts—rather than making predictions. By L23, the representation is polar-leaning but uncommitted, with S at 26.3%, A at 15.4%, and D still only at 3.5%.
perception_phase.context_character: The biochemical context is a polar-rich surface environment with mixed local chemistry. The immediate sequence (GRTLS[D]YNIQK) contains polar (S, T, Y, N, Q) and charged (R, K) residues. Limited structural contacts (only 3) suggest surface exposure rather than buried core positioning.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: only 3 residues within 8Å, insufficient to strongly constrain the prediction
Co-evolutionary signal: none detected (0 co-evolving positions)
Local sequence reading: attention heads at L17-18 (F18:9851, F18:4071) encode the polar-rich immediate context
Representation oscillation: logit lens shows S→H→L→A→S transitions through L1-23, reflecting mixed chemical signals being integrated

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes dramatically at L30-33. At L29, the representation remains diffuse (S at 21.1%, A at 23.0%, D at 5.8%). Layer 30 marks the transition: D jumps to 28.0% as MLP neuron N30:4229 activates (1.17 projection toward D). Layers 31-33 see intense competition—S briefly regains the lead at L31-32 (30.8% and 27.9%)—but the final layer delivers a decisive 39.8 percentage point surge for D (from 27.0% to 66.7%). This is driven by both attention (F33:2787 with 83.0 projection) and MLP (N32:196, N32:783 with 0.83 and 0.77 projections). The model commits to the negatively charged identity despite weak structural evidence.
decision_phase.transition: The L23-25 boundary shows the first signs of decision-making. At L23, the representation is still polar-generic (S at 26.3%, A at 15.4%). Layer 24 introduces aspartate-specific MLP neurons (N24:1241 with 0.31 projection toward D), and L25 continues this trend (N25:1394, N25:2716). However, D remains below 10% through L29. The true transition occurs at L30, where high-confidence prediction channels first activate.

candidates.narrative: Aspartate emerges late but decisively. It remains below 6% through L29, then surges at L30 (28.0%) as MLP neuron N30:4229 activates with 1.17 projection. The final layer (L33) delivers the knockout: a 39.8 percentage point jump from 27.0% to 66.7%, driven by attention feature F33:2787 (83.0 projection) and MLP neurons N32:196 (0.83) and N32:783 (0.77). These are highly specific aspartate prediction channels that override the earlier polar-generic representation.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges at L30 (28.0%), final surge at L33 (66.7%)
key_evidence: N30:4229 (MLP, 1.17 proj) — D-specific neuron with strong P and L votes, activates at L30
F33:2787 (attn, 83.0 proj) — final-layer aspartate prediction channel
N32:196 (MLP, 0.83 proj) — late-stage D writer with E as secondary vote
N31:2506 (MLP, 0.88 proj) — D-specific with P and W as alternatives

candidates.narrative: Glutamate tracks closely with aspartate through the decision phase, reflecting their shared negative charge. E peaks at 18.9% at L30 (when D first surges to 28.0%), suggesting the model is committing to negative charge before selecting the specific acidic residue. E receives support from the same charged-residue prediction neurons (N30:4229 votes for both D and P; N32:783 votes 1.16 for E, 0.77 for D). However, E lacks the final-layer boost that D receives, declining to 10.8% at L33 as D-specific features dominate.
candidates.key_layers: Peaks at L30 (18.9%), declines through L31-33
key_evidence: N32:783 (MLP, 0.77 proj toward D) — votes 1.16 for E, showing charged-residue ambiguity
Tracks D trajectory through L24-30, suggesting shared negative-charge representation
Final decline indicates D-specific features (F33:2787) outcompete generic acidic signal

candidates.narrative: Serine dominates the logit lens from L0 (22.6%) through L26 (46.6%), but this reflects the polar character of the representation being assembled, not a model prediction. The high serine probability indicates the model is encoding the polar-rich local environment (S57, T55 neighbors). Serine's peak at L26 coincides with strong polar-encoding features, but as decision-making begins at L24-25, S starts declining. By L29, S drops to 21.1%, and the final layer reduces it to 4.9%. The model was never predicting serine—it was building a polar representation that happened to project toward S in the logit lens.
key_evidence: Early dominance (22.6% at L0, 46.6% at L26) reflects polar representation character
MLP eraser N25:855 (−0.33 proj) votes strongly for S/T/A, indicating polar-generic encoding
Collapse at L27-33 as charged-specific prediction channels activate

candidates.narrative: Tyrosine remains a minor but persistent candidate, peaking at 27.9% at L32 before declining to 6.4% at L33. Its presence reflects the aromatic residue Y59 immediately adjacent to position 58. Y receives support from late-layer features that encode aromatic context, but lacks the strong prediction channels that D commands. The L32 peak suggests brief competition with D during the final decision phase, but Y-specific neurons are absent from the top writers.
key_evidence: L32 peak coincides with final-layer competition before D surge

candidates.narrative: Histidine spikes dramatically at L3 (29.0%) but this is an early-layer artifact reflecting the model's initial reading of the charged/polar environment. The logit lens projects toward H because the representation at L3 encodes features consistent with charged or polar residues, and H is chemically intermediate (polar with potential positive charge). This is not a prediction—it's the representation's character at a very early stage. H declines rapidly after L4 and remains below 7% for the rest of the forward pass.
key_evidence: Early spike reflects charged/polar representation character, not prediction
No late-layer support from MLP neurons or attention features

turning_points.description: The representation oscillates between hydrophobic and polar character as the model integrates mixed local signals. Serine rises from 22.6% to 46.6%, reflecting the polar-rich sequence context (GRTLS[D]YNIQK). However, this is not a prediction—the logit lens is projecting a polar-generic representation. Attention heads at L17-18 (F18:9851, F18:4071) encode the local sequence, while MLP neurons show mixed votes (N18:3302 votes for D/G/V, N20:3448 votes for E/D/N). The representation is gathering context, not committing to an answer.

The first decision-phase shift occurs as charged-residue features begin activating. MLP neuron N27:2953 (0.52 projection) votes for D/E/N, and N28:2394 (0.48 projection) votes for D/E/C. However, serine still leads at 24.3% at L29, and D is only at 5.8%. The model is transitioning from polar-generic to charged-specific representation, but has not yet committed. Attention head L27:10 erases 2.06 toward D (structural eraser with 0.97 structural attention), suggesting the model is re-evaluating structural constraints.

The decisive phase. Layer 30 sees D jump to 28.0% as MLP neuron N30:4229 activates with 1.17 projection (votes for P/D/L, indicating charged/polar specificity). Layers 31-32 show intense competition—S briefly regains the lead—but L33 delivers the final verdict. Attention feature F33:2787 (83.0 projection) and MLP neurons N32:196 (0.83) and N32:783 (0.77) are highly D-specific prediction channels. The total delta at L33 is 6.39 (4.65 from attention, 3.19 from MLP), driving D from 27.0% to 66.7%. This is the model's final commitment to negatively charged identity.

deep_dives.label: Attention heads L17-18
deep_dives.caption: These heads read the local polar-rich sequence context. L18:9851 and L18:4071 have high projections (26.7, 22.1) and encode the immediate environment (GRTLS[D]YNIQK). This is perception, not prediction—the model is gathering information about what's nearby.

deep_dives.label: SAE features L1-L18
deep_dives.caption: Early features encode sequence identity and local chemistry. F1:9146 and F1:5480 (45.3 projection) capture the initial embedding. F9:5728 (44.3) and F18:9851 (26.7) encode the polar-rich local context. These are not prediction channels—they're building the representation.

deep_dives.label: MLP neurons L24-26
deep_dives.caption: The first decision-phase neurons. N24:1241 (0.31 projection) and N25:1394 (0.33) vote for D, but also for other residues (L, Y, I). These are early, low-confidence votes. The model is beginning to consider aspartate but has not committed.

deep_dives.label: MLP neurons L27-29
deep_dives.caption: Charged-residue features activate. N27:2953 (0.52) votes for D/E/N, N28:2394 (0.48) votes for D/E/C, and N29:2806 (0.54) votes for N/A/D. The model is narrowing toward negatively charged or polar residues, but D is still only at 5.8% at L29.

deep_dives.label: MLP neurons L30-32
deep_dives.caption: The decisive neurons. N30:4229 (1.17 projection) drives D to 28.0% at L30. N31:2506 (0.88) and N32:196 (0.83) are highly D-specific. These are the prediction channels that override the earlier polar-generic representation and commit to aspartate.

deep_dives.label: SAE features L30-33
deep_dives.caption: Final-layer prediction channels. F30:8192, F30:2860, F30:7696 (35.1, 34.8, 34.4 projection) are MLP-sourced features that encode charged-residue specificity. F33:2787 (83.0 projection) is the attention-sourced aspartate prediction channel that delivers the final 39.8 percentage point surge.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts aspartate at position 58 by assembling a polar-rich local context (layers 1-23), then activating charged-residue prediction channels (layers 24-29), and finally committing to aspartate-specific features (layers 30-33). The strongest evidence is the final-layer attention feature F33:2787 (83.0 projection) and MLP neurons N30:4229 (1.17), N31:2506 (0.88), and N32:196 (0.83), which are highly specific to aspartate. Despite weak structural evidence (only 3 contacts, no co-evolution), the model relies on local sequence chemistry to correctly identify this as a negatively charged surface position.
